    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-08-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-08-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="566"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d566">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.42157Sa29/699a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in Canada</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacNider</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-08-26">August 26,
                            1930</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: You are requested to forward a note reading as
                    follows to the Secretary of State for External Affairs:<note n="37"
                        xml:id="d566fn37">The note was communicated to the Canadian Secretary of
                        State for External Affairs under date of September 2.</note>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I have the honor to refer to previous correspondence exchanged between
                            the Government of Canada and the Government of the United States on the
                            subject of the proposed St. Lawrence seaway.</p>
                        <p>“In pursuance of instructions from the President, I desire to reiterate
                            that the Government of the United States stands ready to proceed with
                            this proposed development at the earliest possible date. I have been
                            directed to inquire whether the Canadian Government now finds itself in
                            a position to appoint commissioners to discuss jointly with
                            commissioners of the United States the details of the seaway, and to
                            formulate a treaty appropriate to the purpose.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Very truly yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William R. Castle, Jr.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
